Abstraction — Interview Q&A (Easy → Hard)
Aligned with your Abstraction.py topics: ABC, @abstractmethod, concrete vs abstract methods, abstract properties, instantiation rules, NotImplementedError, payment/plugin designs, and abstraction vs encapsulation.

Level 1: Easy
Q1. What is abstraction in Python?
A: Abstraction means hiding complex implementation details and showing only essential features. Focus on what an object does, not how it does it.

payment.pay(500)   # you care that it pays, not how CreditCard/PayPal works internally
Q2. Why / when do we use abstraction?
A:

Hide complex logic from users
Design large systems cleanly
Enforce a common interface/contract for subclasses
Make code easier to extend and maintain
Q3. How is abstraction achieved in Python?
A: Mainly with Abstract Base Classes (ABC) and @abstractmethod from the abc module:

from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
class Vehicle(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def start(self):
        pass
Q4. What is an abstract class?
A: A class that defines a blueprint/interface and usually cannot be used directly. Subclasses must implement its abstract methods.

class Car(Vehicle):
    def start(self):
        print("Car has started.")
Q5. What is an abstract method?
A: A method declared in an abstract class that must be implemented by concrete subclasses.

@abstractmethod
def start(self):
    pass
Q6. Can you instantiate an abstract class?
A: No. It raises TypeError:

# v = Vehicle()  # TypeError: Can't instantiate abstract class Vehicle...
Q7. What happens if a subclass misses an abstract method?
A: That subclass stays abstract and also cannot be instantiated until all abstract methods are implemented.

class Bike(Vehicle):
    pass
# Bike()  # TypeError
Q8. Give a simple abstraction example.
A:

class Animal(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def eat(self): pass
    @abstractmethod
    def sound(self): pass
class Dog(Animal):
    def eat(self): print("Dog eats bones.")
    def sound(self): print("Woof!")
Q9. Abstraction vs encapsulation?
A:

Abstraction	Encapsulation
Hide complexity / show interface	Hide data / control access
“What it does”	“How state is protected”
ABC, abstract methods	_, __, getters/setters, @property
Q10. Abstraction vs inheritance?
A:

Inheritance — reuse/extend class behavior
Abstraction — define required interface/contract
They often work together: abstract parent + concrete children.

Q11. Real-world abstraction example?
A: Payment system:

class PaymentMethod(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def pay(self, amount): pass
class CreditCard(PaymentMethod): ...
class PayPal(PaymentMethod): ...
class UPI(PaymentMethod): ...
Caller uses pay() without knowing internal payment logic.

Q12. What is a concrete class?
A: A class with no remaining abstract methods, so it can be instantiated (Car, Dog, Rectangle).

Q13. Do users of an abstract API need implementation details?
A: No. They only need the interface:

def process_payment(payment_method: PaymentMethod, amount):
    payment_method.pay(amount)
Q14. What module provides ABC support?
A: abc module — mainly ABC and abstractmethod.

Q15. Can an abstract class have normal attributes?
A: Yes. Example: Shape stores name in __init__ while keeping area abstract.

Level 2: Medium
Q16. Can abstract classes have concrete methods?
A: Yes. Shared/default behavior can live in the abstract class:

class Base(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def foo(self): pass
    def bar(self):
        print("Concrete bar")
Subclasses must implement foo, and can reuse bar.

Q17. Can abstract classes have constructors (__init__)?
A: Yes:

class Shape(ABC):
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name
    @abstractmethod
    def area(self):
        pass
Concrete subclasses call super().__init__(...).

Q18. What is an abstract property?
A: A property that subclasses must implement:

class Shape(ABC):
    @property
    @abstractmethod
    def sides(self):
        pass
class Rectangle(Shape):
    @property
    def sides(self):
        return 4
Q19. Order of decorators for abstract property?
A: Common pattern:

@property
@abstractmethod
def sides(self):
    pass
Subclass implements with @property.

Q20. Abstraction without abc module?
A: Possible with NotImplementedError, but weaker:

class Base:
    def foo(self):
        raise NotImplementedError
Problem: class can still be instantiated; error appears only when method is called. Prefer @abstractmethod.

Q21. Which is safer: ABC or NotImplementedError?
A: ABC + @abstractmethod — fails at instantiation time if contract incomplete. NotImplementedError fails later at call time.

Q22. How does abstraction help large projects?
A:

Consistent interfaces
Plugin-style extension
Lower coupling
Swap implementations easily
Team can work against contracts
Q23. Design exporters (PDF/CSV/XLSX) with abstraction.
A:

class Exporter(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def export(self, data): pass
class PDFExporter(Exporter):
    def export(self, data): print("Exporting PDF")
Loader depends on Exporter.export, not concrete classes.

Q24. Can abstract methods contain code?
A: Yes, though uncommon. Subclasses can call super():

class A(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def foo(self):
        print("Shared logic")
class B(A):
    def foo(self):
        super().foo()
        print("B specific")
Q25. What is an interface in Python terms?
A: Python has no separate interface keyword. ABC with only abstract methods acts like an interface contract.

Q26. Abstraction + polymorphism together?
A: Abstraction defines the common method (pay, start, area). Polymorphism lets different concrete objects respond differently through that same method.

for method in [CreditCard(), PayPal(), UPI()]:
    process_payment(method, 500)
Q27. What error do you get instantiating incomplete subclass?
A: TypeError: Can't instantiate abstract class ... with abstract method ...

Q28. Can one abstract class have many abstract methods?
A: Yes — all must be implemented:

class Animal(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def eat(self): pass
    @abstractmethod
    def sound(self): pass
Q29. Partial implementation pattern?
A: Intermediate abstract class implements some methods, leaves others abstract:

class Vehicle(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def start(self): pass
class FourWheeler(Vehicle):
    def start(self):
        print("Four-wheeler started.")
Or keep some methods abstract in mid-level classes for further subclasses.

Q30. Why annotate payment_method: PaymentMethod?
A: Documents that any object satisfying the PaymentMethod contract is accepted — programming to an interface, not a concrete class.

Q31. Abstraction vs duck typing?
A:

Duck typing — no formal contract; method just needs to exist
Abstraction (ABC) — formal contract enforced by language
ABC is stricter and safer for large systems.

Q32. Risks of poor abstraction?
A:

Inconsistent APIs
Duplication and tight coupling
Hard to extend
More runtime surprises
Weak plugin architecture
Q33. Is every base class an abstract class?
A: No. A normal parent class can be concrete and instantiable. Abstract classes are specially marked (ABC + abstract methods) and meant as incomplete blueprints.

Q34. Mini-project idea with abstraction?
A: Payment processing: abstract PaymentMethod.pay(), concrete CreditCard/PayPal/UPI, and one process_payment() function.

Q35. What does “program to an interface” mean?
A: Write code against abstract contracts (Shape, PaymentMethod) so new implementations can be added without changing callers.

Level 3: Hard
Q36. What is the output?
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
class Vehicle(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def start(self):
        pass
try:
    Vehicle()
except TypeError as e:
    print("Error")
A: Prints Error.

Q37. What is the output?
class Animal(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def sound(self): pass
class Dog(Animal):
    pass
try:
    Dog()
except TypeError:
    print("Dog still abstract")
A: Dog still abstract

Q38. Does implementing only one of two abstract methods make class concrete?
A: No. All abstract methods must be implemented.

class Animal(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def eat(self): pass
    @abstractmethod
    def sound(self): pass
class Dog(Animal):
    def eat(self): print("eats")
# Dog() still TypeError — sound missing
Q39. What is the output?
class Shape(ABC):
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name
    @abstractmethod
    def area(self): pass
    @property
    @abstractmethod
    def sides(self): pass
class Rectangle(Shape):
    def __init__(self, w, h):
        super().__init__("Rectangle")
        self.w, self.h = w, h
    def area(self):
        return self.w * self.h
    @property
    def sides(self):
        return 4
r = Rectangle(3, 5)
print(r.name, r.area(), r.sides)
A: Rectangle 15 4

Q40. Can you use isinstance with ABC?
A: Yes — useful for contract checks:

isinstance(CreditCard(), PaymentMethod)  # True
Virtual subclasses can also register with ABC (register), advanced use-case.

Q41. What is @abstractmethod combined with @classmethod / @staticmethod?
A: Supported patterns exist (e.g., abstract classmethod). Subclasses must provide matching concrete versions. Less common in interviews, but valid advanced ABC usage.

Q42. Abstract method with body + super() — output?
class A(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def foo(self):
        print("Shared")
class B(A):
    def foo(self):
        super().foo()
        print("B")
B().foo()
A:

Shared
B
Q43. Difference between interface-like ABC and mixin?
A:

ABC/interface — defines required methods, often no/little state
Mixin — adds reusable behavior via multiple inheritance, usually concrete methods
Q44. How does abstraction reduce coupling?
A: High-level modules depend on abstract contracts, not concrete classes. You can replace PayPal with UPI without changing process_payment.

Q45. Design a notification system with abstraction.
A:

class Notifier(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def send(self, message): pass
class EmailNotifier(Notifier): ...
class SMSNotifier(Notifier): ...
def notify_all(notifiers, msg):
    for n in notifiers:
        n.send(msg)
Q46. What if abstract class has no abstract methods?
A: Technically possible, but unusual. Without @abstractmethod, inheriting from ABC alone doesn’t block instantiation. Abstractness comes from remaining abstract methods.

Q47. Runtime check vs definition-time enforcement?
A:

NotImplementedError → runtime when called
@abstractmethod → prevented at object creation
Interview preference: ABC.

Q48. How do frameworks use abstraction?
A: Frameworks define abstract hooks (export, handle_request, render). Plugins/apps implement them. Framework calls the abstract API — classic dependency inversion style.

Q49. Abstraction vs polymorphism — one-liner difference?
A: Abstraction defines the common contract; polymorphism provides different behaviors through that contract.

Q50. Predict:
class PaymentMethod(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def pay(self, amount): pass
class CreditCard(PaymentMethod):
    def pay(self, amount):
        print(f"Paid {amount} using Credit Card.")
def process_payment(payment_method: PaymentMethod, amount):
    payment_method.pay(amount)
process_payment(CreditCard(), 500)
A: Paid 500 using Credit Card.

Q51. Can concrete methods call abstract methods in ABC?
A: Yes — template method pattern:

class Worker(ABC):
    def run(self):
        self.step1()
        self.step2()
    @abstractmethod
    def step1(self): pass
    @abstractmethod
    def step2(self): pass
run() is concrete; subclasses implement steps.

Q52. Why is template method an abstraction pattern?
A: Parent defines algorithm skeleton (what), children fill in steps (how) — hides overall flow details behind a stable method.

Q53. Enterprise risk if teams skip abstraction?
A: Every module depends on concrete classes → hard replacements, duplicated conditionals (if paypal... elif upi...), fragile releases, inconsistent APIs.

Q54. Implement Shape hierarchy interview answer.
A:

Abstract Shape with area() (+ maybe sides)
Concrete Rectangle, Circle, Triangle
Client loops over list[Shape] and calls area() only
This shows abstraction + polymorphism together.

Q55. 30-second abstraction interview summary.
A: Abstraction hides implementation and exposes a clean contract. In Python, use ABC + @abstractmethod so incomplete classes can’t be instantiated. Concrete subclasses implement the interface, enabling flexible designs like payments, exporters, and plugins while keeping callers decoupled from details.

